AB  - Consider a small open economy with a Ricardo-Viner (Heckscher-Ohlin) technology in period 1 (2). Period 1 labor is used to produce period 1 consumption goods or period 2 capital goods. Given international borrowing at fixed interest rates, factor price equalization holds. Short-run output and trade patterns are determined by period 1 capital endowments. Long-run outcomes reverse the Rybczynski and Heckscher–Ohlin relationships: a country with relatively large current capital/labor ratios has a low long-run capital/labor ratio and relative output of the relatively capital-intensive good and therefore imports this good. A permanent tariff contracts the protected sector in the short run.
